docs.text: * * * warning - the following review contains spoilers * * *
docs.label: negative

docs.text: cast : gary sinise , don cheadle , connie nielsen , jerry o'connell , kim delaney , tim robbins , elise neal , jill teed , jody thompson , bill timoney written by : jim thomas , john thomas and graham yost directed by : brian depalma running time : 115 minutes
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the first big event movie of 2000 turns out to be anything but .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: gary sinise stars as an astronaut who is removed from a mars mission when his astronaut wife , maggie ( kim delaney ) , becomes ill and passes away .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: don cheadle is then given the mission along with a russian couple and a young hotshot .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: when a strange whirlwind shot from the top of a mars mountain range attacks the crew of the mission , sinise and robbins convince their superior to let them , neilsen , and o'connell perform a rescue mission for whatever crew might be remaining .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: what they discover on the surface of the planet will dramatically change their lives forever ( although no one watching the film will come away profoundly affected ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: before i ever saw the film , i was aware of the promotional campaign with dr . pepper .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: every time i would see a bottle of the soft drink , the mission to mars logo was emblazoned upon it .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: little did i know that the plot would be taking a back seat to the product placement of the drink and several other products .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: dr . pepper saves the day at one point , and a dream sequence/flashback features jerry o'connell shoving m&m's in our face .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: these are but a couple of the ridiculous examples of product placement scattered throughout the film .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: clich ? s are also the order of the day with mission to mars .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: dialogue and character motivations are all lifted directly from countless other science fiction films that have all done it better and with more style ( even independence day , which lifted all of it's premises from other sci-fi films was better than this film , and i don't like independence day ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: films like 2001 : a space odyssey , the abyss , and close encounters of the third kind are all blatantly stolen from ( and poorly at that ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: there is even a sequence where a rover is traveling through a canyon , and i couldn't help but whisper " u'tinni " to myself and wait for a jawa to quickly hide in the rocks before the rover could get a glimpse of it .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this film also features one of my all-time least favorite movie clich ? s : the " he would have wanted you to have this " moment , where one character gives another a trinket that yet another character is established as constantly having ( and is usually made fun of by the character who ends up getting all sappy over it later on ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: scenes like these always bother me when they come out of nowhere in regular films , but in a film as clich ? ridden as this , it is particularly irritating .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: ennio morricone's music is usually considered to be some of the best stuff in the projects he works on , but here it is dreadfully overbearing .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: his music sounds like it came straight out of a vincent price movie in certain scenes .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: at other times his music is unbearably over-dramatic .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: one sequence involving a daring spacewalk rescue is given a particularly cheesy sting when it is discovered that the grappling hook device used for the rescue won't reach its intended target .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: mission to mars is push button filmmaking to the greatest extreme .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: events are set into motion that are obvious to anyone who has ever seen a movie and seem like they are just there to evoke an emotional response in the audience .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: we are apparently supposed to be upset that tim robbins character removes his helmet in deep space and kills himself to save his wife , but i felt extreme boredom coupled with a twinge of disinterest .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: what makes it all worse is that fact that there is no real reason that robbins' character needs to turn himself into a popsicle , except to invoke an emotional response ( i could think of at least one way to save him , and the nasa clowns in this film are supposed to be " smarter " than i am ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: during the finale , when we are finally introduced to the translucent , conehead , kitty-faced aliens that we ostensibly sprung from , we are presented with some of the most ridiculously cartoonish cgi ever put to film ( just slightly worse than the plane crash at the end of air force one or the hell scenes in spawn ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: a brief history lesson about " where we came from " is proffered , then sinise is whisked away to be with " the rest of our people " ( he does this because his late wife proclaims in a video he watches early on that " this is a chance to step foot where no one else has " ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: >from the press i've been seeing this film receive , it is apparent that mission to mars will be dying a quick death at the theater .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i'm sure the first weekend or two will be huge , but once word gets out people will stop going .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: let's just hope the upcoming red planet is better than this and isn't hurt by the negativity this film is generating .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i'd venture to say it won't be worse than this waste of time .
docs.label: negative
